SIMPLE: prorogue
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prorogue
<hw>Pro*rogue"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Prorogued</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Proroguing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>proroger</ets>, L. <ets>prorogare</ets>, <ets>prorogatum</ets>;
<ets>pro</ets> forward + <ets>rogare</ets> to ask, to ask one for his
opinion or vote, or about a law. See <er>Rogation</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To protract; to prolong; to extend.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>prorogued</qex> his government.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To defer; to delay; to postpone; <as>as, to
<ex>prorogue</ex>death; to <ex>prorogue</ex> a marriage.</as></def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To end the session of a parliament by an order of
the sovereign, thus deferring its business.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Parliament was <qex>prorogued</qex> to [meet at] Westminster.</q>
<rj><qau>Bp. Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Parliament was again <qex>prorogued</qex> to a distant
day.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To adjourn; postpone; defer. See
<er>Adjourn</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Proruption</ent>⟦br⟧
